               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18250915-298-person1497">
                  ELIZA 
                  WILKINSON
               <interp inst="t18250915-298-person1497" type="surname" value="WILKINSON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18250915-298-person1497" type="given" value="ELIZA"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18250915-298-person1497" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am the wife of Charles Wilkinson, an <rs id="t18250915-298-viclabel1615" type="occupation">attorney</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18250915-298-victim1496 t18250915-298-viclabel1615"></join>, who lives in <placeName id="t18250915-298-crimeloc1616">Arlington-street</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18250915-298-crimeloc1616" type="placeName" value="Arlington-street"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18250915-298-crimeloc1616" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18250915-298-off1612 t18250915-298-crimeloc1616"></join>, in the parish of St. Pancras. On the 1st of September I had been in the parlour all the morning, and went out of it about a quarter past eleven o'clock; I left this watch, the chain, the seals, key, and a time-piece, in the room - I went into the garden and heard an alarm from the servant - I came back and missed them - I went to the street-door and cried Stop thief! - the prisoner was brought back by some persons, and an officer with him - I saw the officer take the articles from him - they had been on the sideboard, and were worth 24 l.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18250915-298-person1498">
                  ANN 
                  HILL
               <interp inst="t18250915-298-person1498" type="surname" value="HILL"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18250915-298-person1498" type="given" value="ANN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18250915-298-person1498" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am the prosecutrix's servant. On the 1st of September I went out and left the door ajar, and the gate of the front garden open; I went to the next house but one, and returned in about three minutes; I met the prisoner in the passage coming from the parlour - I asked him what he wanted - he asked me the way to Somers' Town; I asked if he went in to ask his way to Somers' Town - he gave me no answer, but ran away directly - I gave an alarm and so did my mistress. I saw him taken up the street, and am sure he is the who person I had seen in the passage.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18250915-298-person1499">
                  WILLIAM 
                  LUMLEY
               <interp inst="t18250915-298-person1499" type="surname" value="LUMLEY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18250915-298-person1499" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18250915-298-person1499" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a coal-merchant, and live in the Hampstead-road. I was in Arlington-street, and saw the prisoner running towards me - he then turned off, and ran towards the brick-fields. I pursued, and said to the brickmaker's who had caught hold of him - "Don't hurt him; let us go before a Justice;" the prisoner said, he had thrown down the time-piece; a boy picked it up, and gave it to me. I then asked him where the watch was - he said, he had thrown that away. I said, "I will not take your word;" I put my hand into his pocket, and found it there - the officer afterwards took it out.</p>
               <p>(Property produced and sworn to.)</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18250915-298-person1500">
                  ABRAHAM 
                  LORIMER
               <interp inst="t18250915-298-person1500" type="surname" value="LORIMER"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18250915-298-person1500" type="given" value="ABRAHAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18250915-298-person1500" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am an officer, and took the prisoner in charge - I took this watch from his left hand waistcoat pocket - the time-piece was given to me.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence (written.) I hitherto have borne an unblemished character, which I have witnesses to prove. I have no wish to palliate my offence, but merely to state, that I was taking a walk with a young man - having no money, and being out of employ, I was persuaded to attempt this robbery - an alarm being made he escaped.</p>
               <p>Two witnesses gave the prisoner a good character.</p>
               <p>
